<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="34310" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="34310">Diagnosis</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="34310">
This species differs from all North American 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Phoridae" genus="Megaselia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Megaselia" order="Diptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="34310" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Megaselia</taxonomicName>
, except those similar to 
<taxonomicName genus="M." lsidName="M. sulphurizona" pageId="0" pageNumber="34310" rank="species" species="sulphurizona">M. sulphurizona</taxonomicName>
, by the contrasting white colour of the posterior abdominal tergites. The lighter coloured halter, stronger ventral abdominal setae (compare with 
<taxonomicName genus="M." lsidName="M. sulphuriza" pageId="0" pageNumber="34310" rank="species" species="sulphuriza">M. sulphuriza</taxonomicName>
, Fig. 4) and the reduced tergite 5 with large posterior setae further distinguish this species.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="34310" type="etymology">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="34310">Etymology</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="34310">Named in memory of Dr. Patricia Bates Simun and Mr. Richard V. Simun by their daughters, Ann and Mary.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="34310" type="distribution">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="34310">Distribution</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="34310">Known only from California, USA (Fig. 6).</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="34310" type="ecology">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="34310">Ecology</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="34310">The habitats at the sites where this species was collected vary from a willow spring in an interior grassland (Wind Wolves), a sycamore/oak forest near a small creek, a coastal floodplain, an old field near the coast, to an inland urban backyard. Many involve at least some exposed water, but this might be simply a reflection of where we put our Malaise traps.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
